ce:section.ce:para:
ROS generation due to photoactivity during the photocatalytic process is known to be one of several factors involved in eARG inactivation [100]. Among them, superoxide and hydroxyl radical have been identified as ROS contributing to DNA damage such as DNA strand breaks [101–104]. Treatment with UVA alone did not result in significant (p > 0.05) production of superoxide or hydroxyl radicals; however, under UVA irradiation at a dose of 0.9 J/cm2, both TiO2 and N,S-CQD-TiO2 significantly (p < 0.05) generated these radicals, with N,S-CQD-TiO2 showing higher levels than TiO2 (Fig. 6
                           ). Fig. 6A shows the quantification of hydroxyl radical (∙OH) generation. Among different N,S-CQD wrapping ratios, 2 % exhibited the highest ∙OH production, followed by 4 %, 1 %, and 6 %. This trend correlates with the eARG inactivation levels, suggesting that ∙OH plays a dominant role. Fig. 6B presents the levels of superoxide radicals (O2
                           −∙), which did not significantly differ across the tested ratios. This suggests that although superoxide radicals were generated, they did not vary significantly among groups and therefore are unlikely to be the main factor responsible for the observed differences in eARG inactivation. Despite UVA's known ability to generate ROS, the absence of ROS production in this study is likely due to the lower dosage utilized, as other studies using UVA doses of 15 or 40 J/cm2 or higher observed ROS production [85,86,105]. Furthermore, the observed ROS generation by TiO2 under UVA irradiation suggests that the formation of banding in previous gel electrophoresis results is indicative of DNA strand breaks caused by ROS generation. Nonetheless, TiO2 exhibited no inactivation effect on eARG in the transformation assay, implying that the damage induced by TiO2 was sufficiently repaired within the cells, thus explaining the absence of inactivation. Notably, irrespective of N,S-CQD wrapping ratios, N,S-CQD-TiO2 exhibited uniform levels of superoxide generation, while variations in hydroxyl radical generation correlated with the observed trends in eARG inactivation rates, indicating that differences in the impacts of N,S-CQD-TiO2 on eARG inactivation can be attributed to differences in hydroxyl radical production.
